<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06341031 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06341031 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; TRADE; REPORT; NEW-YORK; LOS-ANGELES  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Among the more interesting rumors floating through baseball circles as thewinter meetings begin today in Miami is a possible deal between the New YorkYankees and the California Angels centering on pitcher Chuck Finley and secondbaseman Steve Sax.;   The Yankees, who sorely lacked pitching last season,reportedly are willing to deal Sax and his four-year, $12.4 million contract,outfielder Jesse Barfield and a minor league prospect to the Angels for Finley.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  YANKEES MAY TRADE SAX, BARFIELDNEW YORK COULD LAND ANGELS PITCHER FINLEY  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Baseball Notebook  </MEMO><TEXT>     Finley is one of the top left-handed pitchers in baseball, but the Angelshad three 18-game winners and still finished last in their division lastseason. They are willing to break up the threesome that includes Mark Langstonand Jim Abbott.; CHANGE AT THE TOP: The power structure of the Yankees wasjolted when Robert Nederlander announced he will resign as managing generalpartner Dec 31. Nederlander had been in control of the team since Aug. 20,1990, when he succeeded George Steinbrenner as managing general partner.;ETC.: The Pittsburgh Pirates will make one final effort to re-sign Barry Bondsbefore G.M. Larry Doughty begins entertaining trade offers for the All-Staroutfielder. . . . The San Diego Padres want to discuss Benito Santiago'scontract situation, and his agent says that based on the free-agent market theAll-Star catcher deserves a five-year contract. Santiago is eligible for freeagency at the end of the 1992 season. . . . National League President BillWhite has ordered the Miami Marlins to stop hiring employees from the MontrealExpos. The Marlins employ 11 former Expos employees. . . . The Detroit Tigersdeclined to offer arbitration to pitchers John Cerutti and Jerry Don Gleaton,outfielders Pete Incaviglia and Lloyd Moseby, first baseman-outfielder DaveBergman and catcher Mark Salas, making them eligible for free agency.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911206  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  306  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, December 6, 199100341031,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>